author: jsonline
title: State salutes
text:
Jacob Hebior, Westosha Central: The Falcons standout is starting to peak at the right time, posting first-place finishes in each of the past two weeks. On Oct. 2 he won the Kenosha County Championships at UW-Parkside's 5,000-meter course in a season-best time of 16 minutes, 5 seconds. On Thursday he took the title at the Westosha Central Falcon Invitational at Fox River Park in 16:47.0.
GIRLS CROSS COUNTRY Grace Dargiewicz, Waukesha South: The Blackshirts sophomore won the Wolverine Invitational on Thursday, covering the 5,000-meter course at Waterford in a season-best time of 18:55.73. The race was her seventh top-10 finish of the season and second victory. She also won the Waukesha South Cross Country Festival Sept. 19.
FOOTBALL Isiah Wright, Milwaukee Bay View: The Redcats' sophomore quarterback led the team to a 20-16 victory over Milwaukee Bradley Tech on Friday that improved the team to 3-2 in the City Richardson Division and a step closer to guaranteeing their first playoff berth in five years. Wright scored on a 65-yard run in the first quarter and a 6-yard run with 7:39 left in the fourth to give his team the lead for good. He finished with 189 yards in 20 carries and completed 4 of 9 passes for 73 yards.
GIRLS GOLF Stanley Wang, St. Thomas More: The Cavaliers senior reached the state meet as an individual for the second straight season. She arrives in Madison on a roll, having won the Southeast Conference tournament Sept. 24, the regional title Sept. 30 and the sectional crown Oct. 5. At the sectional she shot a 2-over 74 to win at Fox Valley in Kaukauna by four strokes.
BOYS SOCCER Josh Bobke, Oconomowoc: The Raccoons' goalkeeper recorded nine saves to help the post its fourth straight shutout with a 2-0 victory over Catholic Memorial on Friday. He turned away just two shots on Tuesday when the team scored a 1-0 victory over West Bend West that kept the team undefeated in the Wisconsin Little Ten.
GIRLS SWIMMING AND DIVING Cora Meinberg, Hartford: The junior was the only athlete to win three events at the Fondy Invitational on Oct. 3. She won the 50-yard freestyle in 25.12 seconds, took the 100 free in 55.12 and teamed up with Meredith Huber, Lauren Kregel and Carlie DeBack to win the 200 free relay in 1:42.62. Meinberg's 100 time was a season best that ranks 23rd in Division 1. She ranks 14th in the 50 free (25.0).
GIRLS TENNIS Anna Kreynin, Homestead: The Highlanders senior, who fought off two match points and a one-set deficit to win the North Shore title on Oct. 1, took care of business at the sectional Wednesday, finishing ahead of two players who earned seeds for the state meet.
BOYS VOLLEYBALL Jake Christensen, Kenosha Bradford: The Red Devils' strong play in the Southeast Conference continues thanks, in part, to Christensen, a senior outside hitter, who led the team with 11 kills in a 25-17, 25-21, 25-17 victory over Racine St. Catherine's on Wednesday.
GIRLS VOLLEYBALL Jordan Dutkiewicz, Franklin: The senior setter led the Sabers to victories over Racine Park on Tuesday and Pewaukee on Thursday. She had 31 assists, six aces and eight kills in a 25-21, 25-22, 15-8 victory over Park and had 46 assists and three aces in a 25-12, 13-25, 23-25, 25-14, 15-11 non-conference victory over Pewaukee.
